$$A_1 + n \rightarrow A_2 + \sqrt{A_1 A_2} + \frac{1637.3}{m_n c^2} Q,$$

where $A_1$ and $A_2$ are the masses of the parent and product nuclei, respectively, $n$ is the number of neutrons emitted, $Q$ is the released energy, and $m_n$ is the reduced mass of a neutron.

In the case of $^{235}U$, the mass of the nucleus is $A_1 = 235$ u, so $A_2 = 92.5$ u. The released energy $Q$ is given by the equation $Q = mc^2\sqrt{A_1 A_2}$, or $Q = 3.4 \times 10^{12}$ J. Therefore, the energy released per fission of $^{235}U$ is $\frac{Q}{n} = \frac{3.4 \times 10^{12}}{6.022 \times 10^{23}} = 5.6 \times 10^{6}$ J/fission.

